{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.71,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58120"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7402"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43579"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2721"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44218"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58120"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent after a syncopal episode at school yesterday. He lost consciousness for approximately one minute while sitting at his desk. There were no witnessed seizure-like movements. He felt lightheaded beforehand but recalls no other symptoms. He regained consciousness spontaneously and felt tired afterwards. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. There are no focal neurological signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther history reveals three similar episodes in the past six months, all while sitting. There is no history of exercise-induced symptoms. His parent reports that his maternal uncle died suddenly at age 35, but the cause is unknown.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most concerning feature in this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age of presentation","Duration of unconsciousness","Syncopal episodes while sitting","Post-event fatigue","Absence of murmur"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates several red flags that warrant urgent cardiac evaluation. The most concerning feature is the occurrence of \u003Cstrong\u003Esyncopal episodes while sitting\u003C/strong\u003E. Syncope that occurs in a seated position is unusual for benign vasovagal syncope, which typically occurs with prolonged standing or clear triggers. Syncope while sitting raises concern for cardiac arrhythmias or other serious cardiac conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Eage of presentation\u003C/strong\u003E is not particularly concerning, as syncope can occur at any age and is relatively common in adolescents. However, the pattern and circumstances of syncope are more important than age alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eduration of unconsciousness\u003C/strong\u003E of one minute is relatively typical for syncope and does not specifically point toward a cardiac or neurological cause. Most syncopal episodes last less than a minute regardless of cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-event fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E is a common feature of both cardiac and vasovagal syncope and does not help discriminate between causes. It is also common after seizures, making it a non-specific finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of murmur\u003C/strong\u003E does not rule out serious cardiac conditions. Many cardiac causes of syncope, particularly channelopathies like Long QT syndrome, will have normal cardiac examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther concerning features in this case include the family history of sudden death at a young age and the frequency of episodes. The combination of these red flags necessitates urgent cardiac evaluation, even though each individual feature in isolation might be less concerning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple syncopal episodes while sitting is a red flag requiring urgent cardiac evaluation","Family history of sudden death under age 40 is a red flag for inherited cardiac conditions","Absence of prodromal symptoms in syncope is a concerning feature warranting investigation"],"references":["C\u00f4t\u00e9 JM. Syncope in children and adolescents: Evaluation and treatment. Paediatr Child Health. 2001 Oct;6(8):549-51. doi: 10.1093/pch/6.8.549. PMID: 20084125; PMCID: PMC2805591.","Anderson JB, Czosek RJ, Knilans TK, Marino BS. The evaluation and management of pediatric syncope. Pediatr Neurol. 2016;55:6-13."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43579"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T13:54:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T13:56:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7402"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58120"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.